<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-426-632  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 426 632.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  July 11 1989* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Technology Month on automation.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Worsley, Michael; Roowi, S.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     SingaporeTechnologyPolicyAutomationSeminarsm Government.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>TECHNOLOGY MONTH ON AUTOMATION SINGAPORE, S.E.andP;  ASIA, 1989 JUL 4 (NB) --September will be Technology Month in Singapore and Siew Hing Yun, chiefadministrative officer of the Science Council of Singapore (SCS) said thatits theme is automation, as the Economic Development Board (EDB) hasdesignated this year as the Year of Automation.andP;  The SCS is coordinatingTechnology Month, the third in the series.andP;  It is jointly organised by theAutomation Application Centre, EDB, Nanyang Technological Institute (NTI),National Productivity Board, National University of Singapore, Ngee AnnPolytechnic, Singapore Institute of Standards and Industrial Research,Singapore Manufacturers' Association, Singapore Polytechnic and the SingaporeScience Centre.andP;  Technology Month will begin with a symposium onmanufacturing technology at NTI, followed by seminars and exhibitionsreflecting the theme throughout September.andP;  An essay competition to encouragepeople to share their ideas on automation will be one main activity.andP;  The SCSwill present the National Science and Technology award and the National YoungScientist and Engineer awards to local scientists and engineers as marks ofrecognition.andP;  Dr. Tay Eng Soon, Singapore Minister of State for Education,will launch Technology Month, which coincides with NTI's Open Day.andP;  The OpenDay and symposium will focus on the automation research activities of NTI'sstaff and students.andP;  (Michael Worsley andamp; S.Roowi/19890707/Press Contact:Science Council  of Singapore, Ph: (65) 779.7066)</TEXT></DOC>